# Deep Solutions – 3rd Pass (Confidence Defense) — 2025-12-10

Approach: For each gotcha, defend the 2nd-pass confidence by feasibility (API fit, code touch count), blast radius, observability, and rollback ease. Assumes Vertex AI Agent Builder and FastMCP APIs as documented in `origin-docs/Vertex-AI-Agent-Builder-112925` and MCP content contract.

1) Load Agent Engine on startup — Confidence 98%  
- Defense: Uses stable `vertexai.Client.agent_engines.get` call; only adds guarded initialization logic in lifespan. Failure is observable via logs/health; rollback is trivial (feature flag). No API ambiguity.

2) Wrap tool outputs in MCP content format — Confidence 99%  
- Defense: Pure formatting change; MCP spec mandates `content[type=text,text=string]`. No backend dependency; can be unit-tested offline. Zero behavioral risk to logic.

3) Support `/sse/` trailing slash — Confidence 99%  
- Defense: Adds duplicate route decorators; FastAPI accepts stacked paths. No business logic change; failure modes limited to routing conflicts (unlikely).

4) Connectors `search`/`fetch` tools — Confidence 95%  
- Defense: Signatures and response shapes fully specified by OpenAI connectors. Implementation can wrap existing memory/example store or Firecrawl; main risk is schema drift, mitigated by strict schema tests. Work is additive; fallback is to disable if mismatch found.

5) Align MCP protocol version — Confidence 96%  
- Defense: Single constant change to match latest MCP version; low risk if clients accept older values. If incompatibility arises, revertable config toggle.

6) CORS hardening — Confidence 95%  
- Defense: Standard CORSMiddleware knobs; prod-origin allowlist can be tuned without code change. Failure observable via 403/opaque responses. Minimal code surface.

7) Timeouts + operation IDs — Confidence 95%  
- Defense: Uses asyncio timeouts and existing operation handles from Vertex AI; pattern already used for long-running ops. Main risk is client-side polling adoption, mitigated by backward-compatible `wait_for_completion` flag.

8) Scope defaults/derivation — Confidence 95%  
- Defense: Straightforward defaulting (env or session) before calling memory APIs. Risk is mis-scoping data; mitigated by clearly documenting default and allowing explicit override. Easy to feature-flag.

9) Session continuity option — Confidence 95%  
- Defense: Persistence via in-memory/Redis is standard; stateless mode remains default. Blast radius limited to session-enabled deployments. Observability via session logs.

10) Rate limiting — Confidence 95%  
- Defense: Can be implemented via middleware or Cloud Run quotas without touching core logic. Failure mode is throttling, visible in responses/logs. Easy rollback by disabling limiter.

11) Root endpoint — Confidence 99%  
- Defense: Adds a simple FastAPI route returning static JSON. No dependencies; zero logical risk.

12) Vertex connectivity check — Confidence 95%  
- Defense: Optional lightweight ping under env flag with short timeout; isolates failure to health endpoint only. Rollback by disabling flag.

13) Faster SSE keepalive — Confidence 96%  
- Defense: Tunable interval; lowering frequency is safe for bandwidth. Risk limited to server load; mitigated by making interval configurable.

14) Structured error codes — Confidence 95%  
- Defense: Mapping known failure classes to explicit codes/messages; no protocol change to MCP payload container. Risk is misclassification; mitigated by keeping generic fallback and logs.

